    <title>Zoom 2.0 relaunches as an AI-first company without video in its name</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Illustration of the Zoom logo on a blue and black background." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/FgUQohQG4_xDUu5aFMtSRdkD3z0=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73747540/acastro_STK059_zoom_03.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Illustration by Alex Castro / The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="IeZCNG"&gt;Zoom is changing its name from Zoom Video Communications Inc. to just Zoom Communications Inc. In &lt;a href="https://www.zoom.com/en/blog/introducing-zoom-communications-inc/?cms_guid=false&amp;amp;lang=null"&gt;a post on the company blog&lt;/a&gt;, Zoom Communications CEO Eric Yuan writes that Zoom is now an “AI-first work platform for human connection” that delivers “modern, hybrid work solutions.” It’s a muddy, if vague, change compared to its 2020 rise when the classic Zoom Meetings product became synonymous with video conferencing and thrived as companies were forced to transition employees to work from home.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="pplS0u"&gt;Now, it no longer wants to be known for video as workers have returned to offices, and bigger, better-resourced competition from Google, Microsoft, and Slack offers video as a feature of the office suites companies already pay for.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="jL9T3y"&gt;
